<type>(<optional scope>): <subject>

[optional body: explain the motivation and what was changed]

[optional footer: reference issues, e.g., "Resolves #15, See #16"]

# CONVENTIONAL COMMITS CHEAT SHEET
#
# 1. TYPE:
#    - feat     : A new feature
#    - fix      : A bug fix
#    - perf     : A code change that improves performance (short for performance)
#    - refac    : A code change that improves structure/readability without changing external behavior (short for refactor)
#    - ci       : Changes to our CI configuration files and scripts (e.g., GitHub Actions, Travis, Docker workflows)
#    - docs     : Documentation only changes (e.g., README.md, /issues)
#    - style    : Formatting, white-space, missing semi-colons (no code logic changes)
#    - test     : Adding missing tests or correcting existing tests
#    - chore    : Maintenance, build process, or auxiliary tool changes
#    - minor    : Small tweaks or trivial changes that don't fit neatly into other categories
#
# 2. SCOPE (Optional):
#    - The specific component or layer affected.
#    - Examples: (frontend), (backend), (ui), (db), (api)
#
# 3. SUBJECT:
#    - Short summary in the imperative, present tense ("add" not "added" or "adds").
#    - Do NOT capitalize the first letter.
#    - Do NOT put a period (.) at the end.
#
# 4. EXAMPLES:
#    - feat(backend): add GetCommitsBatch endpoint
#    - fix(frontend): resolve infinite render loop in useLatestCommitMap
#    - chore: update issue tracker for #15 and create #16, #17
#    - perf(api): optimize memory allocation during go-git traversal
